slides.title: WHO post
slides.text: This is a map concerning the last months published post from WHO's facebook page. The pink nodes illustrate the post, while the green nodes illustrate who commented on the different post.

slides.title: Zika virus
slides.text: This huge cluster, is one of the clusters concerning the Zika Virus. The post question if there is a treatment and if a travel to a 'Zika zone' is dangerous.

slides.title: Ebola
slides.text: WHO also shared a post concerning Ebola. This cluster is one of the smaller ones, illustrating that the Ebola is not the hottest issue of this month - due to the media coverage.

nodes.label: all known chains of #ebola transmission in west africa have been stopped_ but flare-ups expected. the job is not over - strong surveillance and response systems will be critical in the months to come

cross-border support is key to respond to the health needs of people living in conflict areas. who works around the clock in #syria and complement such efforts from neighbouring countries_ to get emergency health assistance to those in need.

despite significant reductions in the number of maternal and child deaths worldwide_ there has been little change in the number of stillbirths. more than 2.6 million stillbirths occur globally every year_ half of which take place during labour and delivery. the good news? most of these are preventable when high quality_ and timely_ care is provided. see how who is working with the government of #namibia and the european union to bring better quality health care to pregnant women in the country. #endstillbirths

films showing smoking scenes should be rated to protect children from tobacco addiction. big tobacco exploits movies to recruit our children as new smokers. take action against on-screen smoking! #notobacco
globally_ an estimated 1 in 3 infants under 6 months are exclusively breastfed-this needs to be improved! increasing #breastfeeding could save 800_000 children and usd 300 billion every year

great news from world health organization south-east asia region - who searo! the south east asia region today completes five years without any case of wild poliovirus. once considered the most difficult place in the world to eradicate the virus_ #india’s success in eliminating the disease and maintaining its polio-free status for half a decade is a remarkable accomplishment. all efforts must continue until #polio is eradicated globally. let’s #endpolio!

hammad fled #syria with his wife and 3 children in 2012 to escape the horrors of war. many syrian refugees have been forced to leave their homes and seek refuge in #jordan. he survived the war but now battles a chronic disease_ #diabetes_ in a new country. without access to medication_ hammad could die. who supports the ministry of health and other partners in jordan by providing medication_ updating national guidelines and providing training on noncommunicable disease management. photo: who/j. swan

happy new year! we wish you a healthy 2016. in 2015_ who led the health response to major outbreaks and emergencies from west africa to iraq. we provided new advice on a broad range of health issues_ including dementia_ food safety_ hiv treatment_ sugar consumption_ antibiotic resistance and climate change. we marked the end of the 15-year era of the millennium development goals and saw the launch of the sustainable development goals for the next 15 years. here are a few highlights.

how can we best protect non-smokers from exposure to tobacco smoke? there is no safe level of exposure to second-hand tobacco smoke_ but comprehensive smoke-free laws are effective means of eliminating the risks associated with smoking. here is how via who regional office for europe. #notobacco

the #syriacrisis is approaching its sixth brutal year. the health needs are increasing: since the fighting began in #syria_ half of the health workers have left the country. share and show your support to end the suffering of the people

the #walkthetalk: #stepup campaign is officially launched at who headquarters in #geneva_ switzerland_ today. staff are encouraged to take the stairs to get to their offices and to maintain physical activity. what does your workplace do to support staff in staying active?

the global supply of oral #cholera vaccines could double after who approved a third producer_ helping to address global shortages and expand access in more countries. cholera is an acute diarrhoeal disease that can kill within hours if left untreated. there are between 1.4 million and 4.3 million cases a year_ and as many as 142 000 deaths. cholera is endemic in more than 50 countries. #vaccineswork photo: who/l. pezzoli

through the combined effort of governments_ who_ the carter center and other partners_ the number of cases of #guineaworm disease declined dramatically in 2015. from having 3.5 million guinea worm disease cases 30 years ago_ in 2015 there were only 22. we are on the verge of eradicating the disease. we urge development partners to keep supporting the efforts towards eradication_ so we can ensure it happens by 2020.

tobacco still kills around 6 million people each year. there is a way to combat this: a big enough tobacco tax increase could save millions of lives in the next decade. higher taxes help today’s smokers quit. crucially_ they prevent the next generation from taking up smoking in the first place. and they generate revenue that can be reinvested in covering health care costs. #notobacco

today is #worldcancerday. meet abish_ from mexico. in a few months she will mark 5 years free of breast cancer_ thanks to successful treatment. while many nations cannot afford expensive cancer medicines_ #mexico is an example of a middle-income country that has taken major structural steps to ensure people diagnosed with breast and other forms of cancer can access the medicines they need. we can prevent cancer. #wecanican

today is international day of zero tolerance for female genital mutilation. female genital mutilation can have devastating physical_ psychological_ and social consequences for women and girls. health workers can play a crucial role to help end this. let_s empower health workers to #endfgm

what do you want from your #yearsahead? participate in our #instagram campaign with a photo of you – or someone you know – embracing older age and we might feature your photo as part of our campaign. photos can help break down the negative stereotypes that we often associate with #ageing. as the first entries in our instagram campaign to challenge ageism show_ people in older age from around the world continue to enjoy life and play valuable roles in their families and communities. photos can be submitted on instagram or twitter_ using the hashtag #yearsahead_ or sent to healthyageing[at]who[dot]int_ with the subject line: yearsahead. each photo should include a short description_ including where it was taken. make sure that you have the agreement of anyone featured before you post.

what is #microcephaly? as a pregnant woman_ how would i know if my baby is affected? what support would i need if my child has microcephaly? what steps can i take to protect myself and my baby from #zikavirus?
what is #zika? what are the symptoms? how is it treated? should pregnant women be concerned?
what is #zikavirus? is there treatment? should i avoid travelling to areas where #zika virus is occurring? what can i do to protect myself and my family?

who announced today that the recent cluster of neurological disorders and neonatal malformations reported in the americas region constitutes a public health emergency of international concern. this comes after the international health regulation emergency committee agreed that a causal link between this cluster and #zikavirus disease is strongly suspected. it constitutes an “extraordinary event” and a public health threat to other parts of the world.

who calls on all parties involved in the conflict in #yemen to allow the secure movement and delivery of medical and humanitarian aid to all people_ regardless of their location. photo: world health organization- yemen

who director-general margaret chan to convene an international health regulations emergency committee on #zikavirus. the committee will meet on monday 1 february 2016 in geneva to ascertain whether the #zika outbreak constitutes a public health emergency of international concern.

who is currently mapping existing research and development (r&d) for #zika in order to prioritize medical products and approaches that should be fast-tracked into development. diagnostics are a top urgency in order to ascertain the presence of #zikavirus as opposed to other similar diseases like dengue_ chikungunya. photo: epa/d. bockwoldt

who q&as on women_ #zikavirus & possible association with #microcephaly. should pregnant women be concerned about zika virus disease? how can women protect themselves from infection with zika? should pregnant women travel to areas where zika virus is present? can mothers with #zika infection breastfeed their baby?
